ook documents collaborative work, reflecting intense, sometimes controversial, discussions across disciplinary boundaries. In this edited volume, renowned authors explore how exposure to the framework of Cinematic Metaphor inspires their views of metaphor in film and of metaphor theory and analysis more generally. Contributions include explorations from the point of view of applied linguistics (Lynne Cameron), cognitive linguistics (Alan Cienki), media studies (Kathrin Fahlenbrach), media history (Michael Wedel), philosophy (Anne Eusterschulte), and psychology (Raymond W. Gibbs, Jr.).  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCinematic metaphor, audiovisual media, multimodal interaction.1 aCameron, Lynne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCienki, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEusterschulte, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFahlenbrach, Kathrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibbs, Raymond W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreifenstein, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreifenstein, Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHorst, Dorothea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorst, Dorothea, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKappelhoff, Hermann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKappelhoff, Hermann, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMüller, Cornelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMüller, Cornelia, eeditor.4edt4http://i